<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Allenrolfea</i> <i>occidentalis</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub and herbaceous layers with <i>Atriplex</i> <i>canescens</i>, <i>Distichlis</i> <i>spicata</i>, <i>Frankenia</i> <i>salina</i>, <i>Kochia</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Sarcobatus</i> <i>vermiculatus</i>, <i>Sporobolus</i> <i>airoides</i> and <i>Suaeda</i> <i>moquinii</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Allenrolfea occidentalis</i> > 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy, and no other species with greater or equal cover (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b, Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Dry lakebed margins, hummocks, playas perched above current drainages, seeps. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (1996 national list) recognizes <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis</i> as a FACW+ plant. </div>
</div>

        
