<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis </i>is a multi-branched shrub with fleshy, jointed stems. It occurs at seasonally moist or flooded sites, where evaporation concentrates transported salts that create mineral crusts on the soil surface. Plants are tolerant of extreme salinity and heavy soils, which tend to exclude other species, and plants usually form the lowest ring of perennial vegetation around desert salt flats. In contrast to <i>Suaeda moquinii, </i>it is restricted to intermittently saturated substrates. It is more tolerant of high concentrations of salinity and inundation than are <i>Atriplex </i>species (Reid et al. 1999). <br/>
<br/>
In general, stands in the Mojave and Colorado deserts have small, low, and widely to intermittently spaced shrubs. San Joaquin Valley stands have shrubs up to 2 m in height and width. Based on the substantial woody bases of these shrubs, they are old. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
