    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ad, Ai). Stands occur in Carrizo Plain around Soda Lake and range as far north as the Livermore Valley in the Diablo Ranges. Clearing stands for development threaten the northernmost stands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Colorado Desert</b> (322Ca-c). Stands occupy playa borders and adjacent lower bajadas, as well as alkaline terraces above washes, in Anza-Borrego Desert State Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998) and in Coachella Valley (McHargue 1973), where they mix with stands of <i>Atriplex canescens, A. polycarpa,</i> and <i>Sueda moquinii</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Aq, At-w, Ay). San Joaquin Valley stands form fine-scale mosaics with those of the <i>Atriplex polycarpa, Sporobolus airoides,</i> and <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> alliances, depending on depth to water table.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-i, Ak, Am-o). Stands exist in most subsections with descriptions from Death Valley (Bradley 1970) and from central and eastern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004). They are restricted to lowlying alkaline playas and basins.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Di). Stands are known from the vicinity of Fish Slough near Bishop (Odion et al. 1992a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc, Be). In Surprise Valley, stands border the alkali lakes, where they mix with those of <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> and <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> alliances.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sonoran Desert</b> (322Ba, Bc-e). Stands occur around playas (Evens and Hartman 2007) such as Palen Dry Lake and Cadiz Dry Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fc). Stands exist in Saline Valley adjacent to Soda Lake.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands are floristically and structurally simple. Management concerns include direct alteration and disturbance by evaporite mining, as well as blading and scraping for road construction. The fire dynamics in high-cover stands need study. Fire is unlikely in the desert playa stands, but it could be significant in the cismontane stands with high, non-native annual grass cover. </div>
</div>

    

    

